default1.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere seems to be limited evidence that academies per se are having a
default 
defaultgreater impact on narrowing gaps and improving outcomes for disadvantaged pupils. Individual schools make more or less of a difference depending on the quality 
defaultof
default teaching and other intervention strategies to improve outcomes. 
defaultResearch from Machin and Silva (
defaultSchool Structure, School Autonomy and the Tail, Centre for Economic Performance Special Paper No. 29, LSE, 2013
default), suggest that academies had not yet helped low
default attaining pupils.  
defaultThis paper shows that improved attainment centres on higher attainers. It also cites research 
default(Wilson, J (2011) Are England’s Academies more Inclusive or More ‘Exclusive’? The Impact of Institutional Change on the Pupil Profile of Schoo
defaultls. CEE Discussion Paper 125)
default which shows a 12.5% reduction in pupils on free school meals, attending (traditional sponsored) academies compared with the schools they replaced. 
default&#xa0;
default1.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore widely in terms of overall pupil achievement, recent research has found that there is no direct correlation between being an academy and improved attainment levels, reflected in Ofsted judgements.  The critical characteristic to raising attainment in 
defaulta school is the individual capacity of the school leadership. Many sponsored academies are improving the quality of education and pupil outcomes, as they have often replaced very poorly performing schools.  
default&#xa0;
default1.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is interesting to note that research commiss
defaultioned by the L
defaultocal 
defaultG
defaultovernment 
defaultA
defaultssociation (LGA)
default into GCSE results at both academies and maintained schools, published by the NFER in November 2013, 
default(
defaultAnalysis of academy school performance in the 2011 and 2012 GCSEs
default),
default states that academies do not necessaril
defaulty outperform non-academies at GCSE. The study found that in analysing school-level GCSE data since 2007, there is no significant improvement in the rate of improvement of GCSE results for academies over and above the rate of improvement in all schools. It 
defaultsuggested characteristics of a school, such as strong leadership or the quality of teaching, are more likely to be responsible for differences seen, rather than the school's organisational structure.
