defaultQdefaultuestion 2defaultThe process for approving, compelling and defaultestablishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsorsdefault&#xa0;default2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultKent LA has developed a good working relationship with the DfE in managing the conversion of schools that wish to become academies and in making arrangements for some schools 
defaultto be sponsored as academies as a result of poor performance or an inadequate inspection judgement. The LA is now helpfully at a point where 
defaultwe are
default identifying local sponsors for Kent schools that require an academy solution. At the same time the LA has a 
defaultgood working relationship with some, but not all, academy chains that sponsor academies in Kent. It is disappointing that some chains do not respond to our invitation to work more closely together or to offers to help academy chain schools that are still s
defaulttruggling to improve. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn terms of what’s not always working well, we would cite the following issues. The proposed sponsor sometimes makes considerable extra demands upon 
defaultthe LA and its financial and capital resources towards the end of the process 
defaultof
default tr
defaultansfer of a school to an academy chain. 
defaultThis slows down, and can hinder
default the conversion process and can interfere with the urgent school improvement work required.  
defaultThe issuing of an Academy Order can therefore be significantly delayed. In one instance the 
defaultsponsor pulled out at the very end of the process, leaving the school and the local authority without a solution. Sponsors need to be better at due diligence and be committed from the outset.  Considerable public resource and LA Officer time is expended un
defaultnecessarily waiting for sponsors to decide to proceed with their initial interest. The LA is concerned about the lack of engagement at the earliest opportunity regarding new Free School proposals.  As the strategic commissioner of new school provision, the
default LA would welcome early involvement in free school proposals to create new pupil provision in areas of evidenced need.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt present we have five Free Schools open in Kent.  All are in areas of socio-economic advantage, rather than growing diversity and 
defaultchoice in disadvantaged areas of need.  There appears to be ‘middle class capture’ of the Free Schools process, in order to create new capacity in areas that do not necessarily need school places.
default&#xa0;
defaultQdefaultuestion 3defaultThe role of the Secretary of State in intervenidefaultng in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expandsdefault&#xa0;default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is concern about the oversight by the DfE of under-performing and failing academies. The issuing of a warning notice is a limited form of interventio
defaultn and support. In Kent, failing academies do not appear to be being turned around as fast as they should be when they are continuing to perform poorly.  For example, in 2005 a failing secondary high school, in area of socio-economic disadvantage was conver
defaultted to a traditional sponsored academy.  Since that time, it has been the subject of an Ofsted Category twice and to date, the principal sponsor remains and the Academy Trust do not appear to have been transparently held to account by the Secretary of Stat
defaulte.  No Warning Notice has been served on this Academy Trust to date.
