defaultQdefaultuestion 5defaultWhat role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangementsdefault&#xa0;default5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAcademy chains are a 
defaultsignificant player but they are a small part of the education landscape and there are questions about their capacity and track record in bringing about the necessary improvements in poorly performing academies. Some are very successful, some not. It appear
defaults that some academy chains have been allowed to grow without sufficient regard to the quality of the provision they offer.
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn terms of accountability, chains are accountable to their Trust and then the Secretary of State.  There is no local democratic acc
defaultountability, and this lack of transparency and accountability should be addressed.
default There is a need for a proper strategic relationship between the LA as commissioner and the major academy providers (whether national chains or more local groupings
default). This is
default something the LA seeks to achieve on the ground, but the current policy framework is not especially supportive of it.
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe recent announcement by Lord Nash, stating that academy chains will be inspected by Ofsted in the future is welcome, as long as judgements are made about their local impact and their level of accountability to the community they serve.   
